We recommended that Management revisit the accounting and reporting guidelines on the local roads management system as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015 and ––

Direct the General Services Officer to coordinate with the City Planning and Development Officer as well as the City Engineer to update the City’s current road map to facilitate the preparation of proper inventory and reporting of the City’s Road Network Systems and likewise prepare the Report on Local Road Networks as presented in Annex A;

Instruct the City Accountant to coordinate with the General Service Officer in reconciliation of records and likewise maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for the road networks and their corresponding components (road lot, road pavement, drainage and slope protection structures, and other miscellaneous structures) and such ledgers shall be maintained for each local road. Also, require the same to prepare the Local Road Network Ledger Cards (LRNLC) to serve as basis in preparing the lapsing schedule of road network systems and likewise provide additional disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements as presented;

Require the City Engineer to provide the GSO and the City Accounting Office the complete description and cost segregation of the road components as well as assessment of their estimated useful lives as it serves as basis for the latter for valuing the road network items and computing the depreciation of its components;

Direct the members of the Inventory Committee to coordinate with the City Planning and Development Officer in conducting the inventory of local roads under the jurisdiction of the City Government and likewise prepare the Report on Physical Count of Road Network Systems to be submitted to the Office of the Auditor for review and evaluation; and

Require the City Accountant to adjust the erroneous application of depreciation expense through the road lot components by effecting the following entry:

Dr, Accumulated Depreciation–Road Networks  
 P 315,591
Cr. Prior Period Adjustments	
P 315,591

We recommended and the Management agreed directing the accountable officers to submit explanation or justification for non-submission of notice of loss and the corresponding request for relief from accountability, together with the following supporting documents:  

If the occurrence of the loss has also been reported to other police agencies (like the NBI, etc.), the progress / final investigation report thereon should be submitted;

Comment and / or recommendation of the Agency Head concerned on the request;

Exact or accurate amount of government cash or book value of the lost properties; and

Acknowledgement Receipts for Equipment (AREs) covering the lost properties.

Otherwise, the accountable officers / employees concerned should pay the corresponding depreciated replacement costs of the lost properties under their accountability.

We recommended and the Management agreed to ––

a. Direct the General Services Officer (GSO) to:

i.   Include in the annual physical inventory all property, plant and equipment of the City;

ii. Prepare Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to account for all unserviceable and obsolete properties; and

Create a Disposal Committee on the proper disposal of unserviceable properties pursuant to COA Circular No. 89-296 January 27, 1989 and the Supply and Property Management in the Local Government;

b. Direct the City Accountant to:

i. Maintain subsidiary ledgers containing details or breakdown of the balances of all PPE accounts;

Prepare adjusting journal entry on the recognition of impairment losses for the unserviceable properties and another journal entry on the derecognition of these properties after disposal; and

Ensure that all government projects are recognized in the corresponding “Construction in Progress” account and subsequently reclassified to appropriate asset account upon completion;

Conduct regular reconciliation between the Accounting Office and the General Services Office of balances of PPE and other inventory items to ensure accuracy and reliability of balances presented in the Financial Statements; and

Further require the City Accountant and the GSO to account for the reporting difference and undertake necessary adjustments in the books of accounts and in the RPCPPE.

We recommended that Management strictly adhere to Section 5K.02, Article K of the City’s Local Revenue Code of 2008 and COA Circular No. 2015–009 dated December 1, 2015 and ––

Direct the City Treasurer to require the collector assigned in the collection of water bills to issue a separate OR, prepare a separate RCD, and maintain separate cashbook on collections pertaining to initial cash deposits made by new applicants of the WWS services;

Instruct the City Accountant to recognize the initial cash deposits as trust liabilities in the General Fund under the account Customers’ Deposits (2–04–01–050) and likewise prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers thereafter;

Require the City Budget Officer to coordinate with the City Accountant in establishing the total cash deposits that were erroneously treated as revenue for inclusion of appropriations in the Annual or Supplemental Budget, whatever applicable; and

Request the Sangguniang Panlungsod to revisit and review the ordinances pertaining to WWS operations particularly regarding the application of cash deposits for proposal of amendments on certain 

provisions, whenever warranted.

