We recommended that  Management 

Make proper representation with the Sangguniang Panlungsod for authorization and approval on the contracts funded through lumpsum appropriations to ascertain the legality of the succeeding projects to be implemented in accordance with Section 2 of Executive Order No. 189 Supreme Court Ruling in GR No. 175527 dated December 8, 2008;

Through the Local Development Council, identify specific projects to be funded from the 20 per cent LDF, including the use of continuing appropriations, based on the priority needs of the City and likewise discontinue integrating lumpsum appropriations so that the projects in the AIP will be fully implemented within the year.

We recommended that Management revisit the guidelines in operating the IAS/U prescribed by DBM LBC No. 110 dated June 10, 2016 through the Internal Audit Manual for LGUs and ––

Define the Unit’s duties and responsibilities and detach the same from conducting pre-audit and routinary functions. Instead, institute and conduct a program of internal audit for the City to ensure that government spend within what is required, invests in the right priorities, and has measures of organizational performance that are well-defined;

Submit a proposal to the Sangguniang Panlungsod for the establishment of the IAS/U in the City, as well as its inclusion in the organizational structure, functional charts, personnel complement, and operating budget;

Direct the HRMO to institute a well-defined personnel complement to be assigned at the IAS that conforms to the organizational structure prescribed by the IAM as well as the qualification standards required by CSC Memorandum Circular No. 12–2006 dated June 22, 2006; and

Grant the personnel assigned in IAS/U the complete access to LGU records as well as opportunities to trainings and seminars particularly regarding compliance with prevalent laws and regulations in order to equip them with the necessary knowledge, skills, and competencies required to effectively institute measures in safeguarding of government funds as well as institute policies and procedures to further improve the City’s operations as a whole.

We recommended that Management:

Direct all JO employees to strictly com-ply with Sections 1 to 5 of CSC Memorandum Circular No. 01, s. 2017;

Strictly require all JO employees assigned in the SP Office to time in and out using the biometrics ma-chine and report to work from 8:00 AM to 12:00 PM and from 1:00 PM to 5:00 PM from Monday to Friday to ensure that the amount of wages paid by the government is based on the services they rendered and prevent any doubts of having ghost emplo-yees; 

Limit the hiring of JOs to three (3) per SP Member and refrain from hiring immediate family members as JO;

Instruct the SDO to immediately stop the practice of releasing the wages to person other than the claimant based on an authorization letter with-out valid reason ex-cept in very exceptional cases wherein the concerned claimant cannot come in per-son under the power of attorney.

